\noindent\textbf{[2019 May/June, 0580/43, Question 4]}\par

\begin{parts}
\item
%\begin{InsertScreenShot}
%    \relincludegraphics{Figures/Q04-HemisphereCylinder.png}
%\end{InsertScreenShot}

The diagram shows a hemispherical bowl of radius 5.6 cm and a cylindrical tin of height 10 cm.

\begin{subparts}
\item Show that the volume of the bowl is 368 cm$^3$, correct to the nearest cm$^3$.

\[\left[ \text{The volume, } V, \text{ of a sphere with radius } r \text{ is } V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3. \right]\]

\Marks{2}

\item The tin is completely full of soup.
When all the soup is poured into the empty bowl, 80\% of the volume of the bowl is filled.

Calculate the radius of the tin.

\AnswerLine[][\text{cm}]
\Marks{4}
\end{subparts}

\item
%\begin{InsertScreenShot}
%    \relincludegraphics{Figures/Q04-Cone.png}
%\end{InsertScreenShot}

The diagram shows a cone with radius 1.75 cm and height 6 cm.

\begin{subparts}
\item Calculate the total surface area of the cone.

\[\left[ \text{The curved surface area, } A, \text{ of a cone with radius } r \text{ and slant height } l \text{ is } A = \pi rl. \right]\]

\AnswerLine[][\text{cm$^2$}]
\Marks{5}

\item The cone contains salt to a depth of 4.5 cm.
The top layer of the salt forms a circle that is parallel to the base of the cone.

Show that the volume of the salt inside the cone is 18.9 cm$^3$, correct to 1 decimal place.

\[\left[ \text{The volume, } V, \text{ of a cone with radius } r \text{ and height } h \text{ is } V = \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h. \right]\]

\Marks{4}

\item The salt is removed from the cone at a constant rate of 200 mm$^3$ per second.

Calculate the time taken for the cone to be completely emptied.
Give your answer in seconds, correct to the nearest second.

\AnswerLine[][\text{s}]
\Marks{3}
\end{subparts}
\end{parts}

